<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-420-110  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 420 110.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  April 30 1990 v9 n9 p78(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GSBCA clarifies rules in protesting sealed bid award. (GeneralServices Administration Board of Contract Appeals) (Fedwatch)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dornan, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. General Services Administration. Board of ContractAppealsGovernment ContractsGovernment AgencyProceduresLegal Issues.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>GSBCA Clarifies Rule sin Protesting Sealed Bid AwardandM;The General Services Administration Board of Contract Appeals has mandatednew procedures for agencies defending against sealed bid protests.andM;The U.S.andP;  Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit recently ruled that onlybidders next in line for award may protest under a scaled bid procurement.andO;In decision 10517-P of March 5, the GSBCA established new procedures foragencies to use when responding to protests from bidders not obviously nextin line for award.andM;First, the protester must claim that the winning bid and all other bids aheadof its bid are nonresponsive.andP;  Therefore, if the protester prevailed, itwould win the contract.andM;The protest does not have to contain specific details supporting this claim,but the protester will have to prove the charges during protest resolution.andM;The agency immediately must make a good-faith effort to evaluate allintervening bids for responsiveness before it can challenge the protester'sstanding.andM;The agency must give copies of the evaluation to the GSBCA and to theprotester early in the protest process.andP;  The burden is on the protester torefute the agency's determination that any intervening bid is responsive.andM;To ensure the fairness of the agency's determination, the agency must providethe protester access to all intervening bids within 24 hours of the order.andO;The protester then has three complete days to examine the bids and to submita detailed statement about why these intervening bids are nonresponsive.andM;After receiving the protester's statement, the agency has two days to makeits final determination.andM;Agency procurement offices now must gear up to respond immediately to thiskind of review of bid award decisions.andP;  The agency may want to evaluate thefirst three or four bids for responsiveness to establish some limits on whocan protest.andM;Bidders also should review the bids of all intervening bidders -- not justthe awardee -- at bid opening to determine responsiveness.andP;  This process willadd significant new requirements on an already overburdened procurementcommunity.andM;Bob Dornan is vice president of Federal Sources Inc., Vienna, Va.andO;</TEXT></DOC>